                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.24/1626</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Adviser on Political
                        Relations</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-18">July 18,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Hall called on me at his request in continuation of conversation begun on
                    July 16. Mr. Hall said that the British Government expected to be very
                    conservative about putting embargoes on foodstuffs in trade with Japan; that it
                    was giving “further study” to certain commodities, especially: iron ore, lead,
                    zinc, bauxite, manganese, salt, mica, fluorspar and copra from New Guinea; and
                    that it was especially interested in the subject of bunker control in the
                    Pacific.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">tanley</hi>] K. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >ornbeck</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
